ant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Furnell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","variant of   Furneaux  .","alternatively, perhaps a variant of   Farnell  . Compare   Funnell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Furneaux","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from either of two places in Normandy called Fourneaux ‘(the) furnaces’, one in Manche, the other in Calvados. Compare   Furnace   and   Furnell  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":11,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":21,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":31,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert De Furnell was born in 1075, in Drayton, Leicestershire, England. He married Mrs Robert De Furnell before 1100, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1146, in his hometown, at the age of 71."},"et":{"1075–1146":"1075–1146","–Female":"Surnud","1104–1132":"1104–1132","1106":"1106","1104":"1104","1146":"1146","before 1100":"enne 1100","Abt 1132":"umbes 1132","1132":"1132","1075":"1075","Abt 1104":"umbes 1104","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","Thrapston, Northamptonshire, England":"Thrapston, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Drayton, Leicestershire, England":"Drayton, Leicestershire, England"},"fi":{"1075–1146":"1075–1146","–Female":"Kuollut","1104–1132":"1104–1132","1106":"1106","1104":"1104","1146":"1146","before 1100":"ennen vuotta 1100","Abt 1132":"noin 1132","1132":"1132","1075":"1075","Abt 1104":"noin 1104","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","Thrapston, Northamptonshire, England":"Thrapston, Northamptonsh